Demographic Issues in PLAICRAFT AI's Research Project¶

Equality as a 'Building Block' for Better AI-powered NPCS¶

Introduction¶

In September of 2023, AI Researchers at UBC launched a “free Minecraft in the cloud” AI research data collection project. The project aims to collect 10,000 hours of freely volunteered play time. Using this data, the lab hopes to create artificially intelligent non-player characters in Minecraft that act like real people. These NPCs would respond to both visual and auditory stimulus, and be able to play in various game modes just like real people (Smith 2023).

Minecraft, a video game released in 2009, has taken the world by storm due to its limitless "sandbox game" design. There is no one right way to play. Minecraft can be played alone or in groups, with friends or online, passively or violently. Some game modes involve survival of the fittest, while others, such as "Creative" mode, use the game to build whatever the user wants (Landin 2023).

Research has shown different demographics approach playing video games differently. Due to literacy and generational conventions, different age-groups use in-game chat features differently (Ames and Burrell 2017); In studies examining gender differences, girls often played more collaboratively and patiently, while boys were drawn to objective-oriented gameplay modes (Yeh, Lan, and Lin 2018).

Minecraft is a diverse game. It makes sense that demographic differences would be refected in users' choices and approaches to limitless options.

If PLAICRAFT AI aims to make realistic non-player characters, the demographic of its research should be equitable and diverse– and by extension, include all types and approaches to gameplay. We were provided with a dataset which contained seven observations about each of its 196 unique players. Using this data, our investigation seeks to better understand the demographic of participants in the research project so far, and ultimately to highlight biases and deficits that might skew the behaviour of PLAICRAFT's AI-Powered NPCs.

More specifically, we'd like to know:

Can factors such as self-described experience, age, and subscription to a gaming-related newsletter successfully predict the gender of players in this dataset?

To investigate this classification problem, we will use a k-nearest neighbors algorithm.

If the KNN model can accurately predict gender, it suggests there are consistent, gender-based patterns in the dataset. Since this survey was a preliminary understanding of traits of different gamers, a successful model might suggest that different gender demographics have fundamental differences in how they engage with the PLAICRAFT project overall.

If there are demographic differences, it would be especially important different social groups are all equally repersented in the project's research stage. Otherwise, PLAICRAFT risks creating an AI which is biased in its behaviour to the groups which participated the most.

Exploring the dataset in a glance¶

We can now see that our dataset, Players, consists of five columns, with 196 unqiue observations.

Experience: a factor, either Beginner, Amateur, Pro or Veteran
Subscribe: a boolean, either true or false: are users subscribed to
played_hours: a double, the number of hours a player contributed to the project through playtime
gender: a string, the self-identified gender of a player
Age: an integer, the age of a player

We can now start to better understand the responses in our dataset, through some simple calculations and graphs.

Evaluating our graphs¶

Looking at these graphs we can learn a few things about the data collected in this dataset. Figure 3 shows us most players identify as amateur but there is a fairly even spread of skill levels in our data set. In Figure 5 we can see age is a skewed distribution with a significant peak at 15-20, probably because a majority of participants were undergraduate college students. There are some outlying values in the adult range. Figures 2 and 6 reveal most players are subscribed to the newsletter and are male– almost 75% in each category.

Figure 4 reveals that play time is a significantly skewed distribution, with most players only playing for a few minutes. When considered in context, this means most players aren't engaging with PLAICRAFT fully– rather, they come on, get comfortable with the features, and then stop using the server. The mean is skewed by some extreme outliers, including a few players that played for hundreds of hours. The implications of the lack of overall playtime from most players is significant. It might suggest that the AI is biased towards the behaviours of players while they orient themsleves to their surroundings at the beginning of the game, rather than actual gameplay behaviour. Alternatively, the AI may be biased towards the behaviours of the few individuals who did play for hundreds of hours.

Methods and Results - K-NN Analysis¶

Can factors such as self-described experience, age, and subscription to a gaming-related newsletter successfully predict the gender of players in this dataset?¶

To apply a KNN algorithm, we begin by mutating the gender column into a factor variable to categorize players' gender.

We then have to make sure our other values are all numeric. To do so, we decided to assign a numeric score to experience levels. Experience goes from being either "Beginner," "Amateur," "Pro," and "Veteran", to an integer from 1 to 4, where 1 represents the most beginner level and 4 indicates the most advanced experience.

Similarly, we transform the subscribe column into a binary numeric scale, with 0 indicating non-subscription and 1 indicating subscription. After removing any missing values, our dataset is clean and ready to analyze!

In [103]:
#experience is now scored from 1 to 4, with 1 being the most beginner and 4 being the most advanced
#subscription is now scored from 0 to 1, where 0 is not subscribed and 1 is subscribed
players <- players |>
            mutate(gender = as.factor(gender)) |>
            mutate(experience = as.numeric(factor(experience, 
                                              levels = c("Beginner", "Amateur", "Pro", "Veteran")))) |>
            mutate(subscribe = as.numeric(subscribe))

players <- drop_na(players)

Now, we set a random seed or reproducibility and use the initial_split function to divide the sample into training and testing datasets. We chose an 80% training and 20% testing split, per the recommendation of a TA. The split was stratified by gender to ensure balanced representation in both sets.

In [104]:
set.seed(1234) 

#splitting data into testing and training, using the proportion reccomended by TA as feedback to proposal 
gender_split <- initial_split(players, prop = 0.80, strata = gender)
gender_train <- training(gender_split)   
gender_test <- testing(gender_split)

We now split our dataset for cross validation using 5 folds and the vfold function, with stratification again by gender. Using these folds allows us to assess the model’s generalizability without excessive computation. We also create a tibble of possible k-values we want to analyze, ranging from 1-10, to evaluate in our tuning.

Our end goal here is to use cross-validation to find the optimal number of neighbors for our model. Cross-validation will test how well each model, with each k-value, works; it'll train on part of the given data and checking the results on the rest, then repeat this several times to get an average result.

In [105]:
set.seed(1234) 
vfold <- vfold_cv(gender_train, v = 5, strata = gender)
k_vals <- tibble(neighbors = seq(from = 1, to = 10, by = 1))

To perform our K-NN analysis, we create a recipe that states we want to find the gender of a datapoint using the experience level, subscription status, and age as predictors. We provide our recipe the training data, and then scale and center all metrics to avoid one variable having a larger or smaller influence on our algorithm than another.

We create a K-NN model that's prepared to tune its K-value rather than have one set in stone. We then add our recipe and this tuning model together in a workflow. Our K-NN model runs 10 times for each of our K-Values, using 5-fold cross-validation, and returns a tibble of metrics collected in the process.

In [106]:
gender_recipe <- recipe(gender ~ experience + subscribe + Age, data = gender_train) |>
                step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
                step_center(all_predictors())

knn_tune <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) |>
                set_engine("kknn") |>
                set_mode("classification")


knn_results <- workflow() |>
      add_recipe(gender_recipe) |>
      add_model(knn_tune) |>
      tune_grid(resamples = vfold, grid = k_vals) |>
      collect_metrics()

Using these metrics, we filter specifically for accuracy and store it in its own data frame. We can now visualize the relationship between the number of k-neighbors and the accuracy estimate of the algorithm.

In [113]:
accuracies <- knn_results |> 
      filter(.metric == "accuracy")

accuracy_versus_k <- ggplot(accuracies, aes(x = neighbors, y = mean))+
      geom_point(color = "deepskyblue4") +
      geom_line(color = "deepskyblue") +
      labs(x = "Neighbors", y = "Accuracy Estimate") +
        ggtitle("Figure 9: Accuracy of Algorithm v. K-Value") +
        theme(text = element_text(size = 24))


accuracy_versus_k

Figure 9 has a peak in accuracy at k = 9, which suggests that this is the optimal value for our k-NN model between 1 and 10.

(It's worth noting that while the scale of our model makes the increase in accuracy look quite steep, from k = 1 to k = 9 our model's accuracy only really increases 25%. This a notable, but not monumental, amount.)

Using the results of Figure 9 we proceed to set k = 9 for our final model's specification. We then fit the model to training data using the same recipe from before and our new model specification.

Using this, we can predict the gender outcomes on the test data. The predictions were combined with the the original test dataset into one dataframe for comparison, which now contains both predicted and actual gender values.

In [108]:
gender_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = 9) |>
      set_engine("kknn") |>
      set_mode("classification")

gender_fit <- workflow() |>
      add_recipe(gender_recipe) |>
      add_model(gender_spec) |>
      fit(data = gender_train)

gender_test_predictions <- predict(gender_fit , gender_test) |>
      bind_cols(gender_test)

The accuracy of the model on the test data was calculated using the metrics function, comparing predicted and actual gender values. The resulting accuracy is 0.7407, as in 74.07% of our models' predictions of gender are correct.

Discussion¶

Through this analysis of data provided through the PLAICRAFT AI research project, we explored the question: “Can factors such as self-described experience, age, and subscription to a gaming-related newsletter successfully predict the gender of players in this dataset?”

To answer this, we developed a K-NN classifier.

Results of the Algorithm - was this what we expected?¶

Our classifier achieved an accuracy of 74% using a k-nn neighbors algorithm of k = 7.

Generally, this affirms our research question, and was what was expected. By knowing other information about participants in the survey, we could relatively accurately guess their gender identity. This makes sense when we consider the visualizations and explorations of the data from earlier in this report. Notably, self-reports of expertise, for example, do not seem to be independent of gender identity. These relationships were predicted to be useful to an algorithm in classifying a player's gender correctly.

Potential Issues¶

It is worth noting that the skewed distribution of genders is a notable source of error in our algorithm. When answers other than male or female were removed from the dataset, we ended up with a total count of 161 players– of which 124 were male– or 77%. Note how close this is to the accuracy percentage of our K-NN model. The overrepresentation of men is why there is such a generally steep and positive slope to Figure 9, our graph of K v. Accuracy.

An algorithm which includes more data points as nearest neighbors would become more and more likely to predict every gender to be the mean of the dataset, or male. It can be understood that our algorithm does something similar, predicting nearly every datapoint to be male as k increases. This is due to the extreme bias in the dataset. Even if our algorithm always predicted male, it would still be successful 77% percent of the time.

Theoretically, we could fix issues with our biased dataset and the K-NN model by artificially "upsampling" the minority classed data points (in this case, female). This would mean duplicating the female datapoints we already had, and treating them as new data points, as if more women were surveyed.

However, our data set is tiny. Women make up such a small proportion of the data, and are not distributed the way we would expect the entire population to be, which is shown in the uneven spread of experience level, for example. The extent to which upsampling would then be a reliable representation of the greater population which the project seeks to represent is limited.

The small size of our dataset also raises questions about the reliability of our training and testing data. With less than 200 data points, our training sample was made up of only around 30 unique data points. Generally, the more data, the better the results of our K-NN algorithm could be. With such a small and biased sample the reproducibility of our research remains unclear.

Future Lines of Inquiry and Questions¶

Does over-representation of one demographic actually create biased NPC behavior in actual gameplay?

How could engagement be increased for underrepersented demographics in our sample? What factors encourage or discourage their participation?

What other traits of video game players can be predicted using classification?

Impact of Research and Potential Solutions¶

PLAICRAFT AI seems to be struggling with data collection from several perspectives. Not only is data skewed in gender, but playtime rarely exceeds six minutes.

Our recommendation to fix this is to target 100- and 200- level computer and data science courses at the University of British Columbia and encourage their participation in the project! In these introductory level courses, the population of students is large and gender distributions are reflective of the general population. Instructors could offer one, synchronous class worth of Minecraft playtime for extra credit. If everyone in the class plays together, useful and meaningful data about player behaviour and collaboration can be observed over a sustained period of time.

As it currently stands, the biased dataset of PLAICRAFT AI risks its integrity and purpose. To succeed at its end goal of creating realistic non-player characters, the project needs to alter its data collection methods, to focus on both gender equality as well as collecting longer and more valuable play sessions. Not only will this mitigate bias in the data, but it would embrace the spirit of Minecraft– which in its core, is a game for everybody.
